1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,910
If we have a library of books,

2

00:00:01,910  -->  00:00:04,230
we could be dealing with thousands or

3

00:00:04,230  -->  00:00:08,350
even tens of thousands or even hundreds of thousands of books,

4

00:00:08,350  -->  00:00:10,130
articles, and media items.

5

00:00:10,130  -->  00:00:13,370
There is no way that we have time to individually

6

00:00:13,370  -->  00:00:16,970
go through each item by hand, would take forever.

7

00:00:16,970  -->  00:00:20,730
That's where we'll want to iterate through dictionaries like this,

8

00:00:20,730  -->  00:00:26,330
so that we can go through our key value pairs without spending excessive time and worry.

9

00:00:26,330  -->  00:00:31,870
If we wanted to loop through all of the key value pairs in a dictionary for our library,

10

00:00:31,870  -->  00:00:35,210
we can rely on our trusty for loop to help us out.

11

00:00:35,210  -->  00:00:40,270
We can loop through a dictionary to access its keys, values or both.

12

00:00:40,270  -->  00:00:42,405
Let's see an example of this.

13

00:00:42,405  -->  00:00:47,460
Let's talk about iterating through dictionaries and their keys and values.

14

00:00:47,460  -->  00:00:52,370
First, we'll build out a dictionary which we will set as library,

15

00:00:52,370  -->  00:00:55,970
and this library will consist of three items.

16

00:00:55,970  -->  00:00:58,190
There will be pride and prejudice,

17

00:00:58,190  -->  00:01:00,810
which is set as the romance genre,

18

00:01:00,810  -->  00:01:04,110
1984, which is the dystopia genre,

19

00:01:04,110  -->  00:01:07,065
and then Moby Dick, which is the adventure genre.

20

00:01:07,065  -->  00:01:10,005
It's a list of titles and genres.

21

00:01:10,005  -->  00:01:14,995
When we print our library,

22

00:01:14,995  -->  00:01:19,650
we'll see those three items printed here as well on one line.

23

00:01:19,650  -->  00:01:22,270
If we wanted to loop through all the keys,

24

00:01:22,270  -->  00:01:25,110
we can do this by looking for book,

25

00:01:25,110  -->  00:01:28,610
our arbitrary counter element in library,

26

00:01:28,610  -->  00:01:33,770
the dictionary we just declared and then tell our for loop to print the counter element,

27

00:01:33,770  -->  00:01:38,830
and we'll do that by saying for book in library.

28

00:01:38,830  -->  00:01:43,190
Remember this is our increment for item in library,

29

00:01:43,190  -->  00:01:45,850
which is our dictionary.

30

00:01:45,850  -->  00:01:49,010
We'll then say print book.

31

00:01:49,080  -->  00:01:52,460
When we execute this, we'll see all three titles,

32

00:01:52,460  -->  00:01:55,980
Pride and Prejudice, 1984, and Moby Dick.

33

00:01:56,300  -->  00:02:01,620
Now, what if we wanted to print out the genres of the library?

34

00:02:01,620  -->  00:02:03,740
We would do the same thing but for this,

35

00:02:03,740  -->  00:02:06,700
we can change the arbitrary counter to genre,

36

00:02:06,700  -->  00:02:13,060
and then we need to use the dot values method off of the library dictionary.

37

00:02:13,060  -->  00:02:15,480
We'll learn about this in a second,

38

00:02:15,480  -->  00:02:20,540
but notice how we can now increment with the second value rather than the titles,

39

00:02:20,540  -->  00:02:24,005
which is the first item and we'll do that by taking

40

00:02:24,005  -->  00:02:27,600
our for loop from the previous step and modifying it so slightly.

41

00:02:27,600  -->  00:02:30,890
We can just change this to any name,

42

00:02:30,890  -->  00:02:33,780
but we'll say genre and then we'll say in

43

00:02:33,780  -->  00:02:39,240
library dot values because we're looking at the second element.

44

00:02:39,240  -->  00:02:42,240
This is the key and this is the value.

45

00:02:42,240  -->  00:02:45,195
Now we're looking at just the values here.

46

00:02:45,195  -->  00:02:50,165
Then when we print book but genre,

47

00:02:50,165  -->  00:02:55,040
this will now print out, romance,

48

00:02:55,040  -->  00:03:01,000
dystopia, and adventure, which are the three genres in our library right now.

49

00:03:01,280  -->  00:03:03,900
To wrap up incrementing,

50

00:03:03,900  -->  00:03:07,240
if we wanted to cycle through both the key and the value,

51

00:03:07,240  -->  00:03:10,720
we can use another method called items which we'll

52

00:03:10,720  -->  00:03:15,340
also learn about momentarily to go through multiple items.

53

00:03:15,340  -->  00:03:21,960
For our for loop, we can just string these multiple items together as book genre,

54

00:03:21,960  -->  00:03:27,190
meaning, for book and genre in our library of items, print the values.

55

00:03:27,190  -->  00:03:30,450
What we'll do is we'll say, for book,

56

00:03:30,450  -->  00:03:35,630
genre in library items.

57

00:03:35,630  -->  00:03:37,840
Colon, we'll say print,

58

00:03:37,840  -->  00:03:40,040
and we'll use another f string,

59

00:03:40,040  -->  00:03:45,135
pass in squiggly bracket and say book,

60

00:03:45,135  -->  00:03:50,205
and then another set of squiggly brackets, and we'll say genre.

61

00:03:50,205  -->  00:03:52,180
We'll close out that f string,

62

00:03:52,180  -->  00:03:54,120
close out the parenthesis.

63

00:03:54,120  -->  00:03:58,080
Now, can you guess what this will output when we run this?

64

00:03:59,000  -->  00:04:02,650
It will now print out each has a string.

65

00:04:02,650  -->  00:04:04,935
Pride and prejudice for romance,

66

00:04:04,935  -->  00:04:08,685
1984 for dystopia, and Moby Dick for adventure.

67

00:04:08,685  -->  00:04:16,440
We're iterating over the keys and the values of our library. Pretty neat, right?
